  "local_port": 42406,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the rules for Yahoo's fantasy hockey?",
  "response": "Yahoo Fantasy Hockey is a popular platform that allows users to create and manage their own fantasy hockey teams by drafting real NHL players and competing against other managers based on those players' real-life performances. While specific settings can vary depending on the league customization, here's an overview of the common rules and features you can expect in a standard Yahoo Fantasy Hockey league:\n\n### **1. League Formats**\n- **Head-to-Head (H2H):** Teams compete against a different opponent each week, earning points or wins based on statistical performance.\n- **Points:** Players accumulate points based on their real-life performance, and the team with the most points each week wins.\n- **Rotisserie (Roto):** Teams are ranked in various statistical categories, and points are awarded based on standings in each category at the end of the season.\n\n### **2. Draft Types**\n- **Snake Draft:** Teams take turns selecting players in a \"snaking\" order, reversing the order each round.\n- **Auction Draft:** Managers have a budget to bid on players, with each player going to the highest bidder.\n- **Auto Draft:** If not all teams are present, players are automatically drafted based on pre-set rankings.\n\n### **3. Roster Composition**\nTypical roster positions include:\n- **Forwards:** Center (C), Left Wing (LW), Right Wing (RW)\n- **Defensemen:** Defense (D)\n- **Goaltenders:** Goalies (G)\n- **Bench Spots:** Reserve players who can be substituted into the lineup\n- **Utility Spots:** Flexible positions that can accommodate any position type\n\n### **4. Scoring Categories**\nCommon scoring categories in Yahoo Fantasy Hockey include:\n- **Forwards and Defensemen:**\n  - Goals (G)\n  - Assists (A)\n  - Plus/Minus (+/-)\n  - Power Play Points (PPP)\n  - Shots on Goal (SOG)\n  - Hits (HIT)\n  - Blocked Shots (BLK)\n\n- **Goaltenders:**\n  - Wins (W)\n  - Losses (L)\n  - Goals Against Average (GAA)\n  - Save Percentage (SV%)\n  - Shutouts (SO)\n  - Shots Against (SA)\n  - Saves (SV)\n\n### **5. Transactions**\n- **Waiver Wire:** Players not currently on a team can be claimed by managers. The waiver priority typically determines the order in which teams can claim players.\n- **Free Agents:** Players not on any team and not on waivers can be added directly.\n- **Trades:** Managers can trade players with other teams, subject to league approval and trade rules.\n\n### **6. Playoffs**\n- **Duration:** Typically occur during the final weeks of the NHL regular season.\n- **Format:** The top teams in the league standings compete in a bracket-style tournament to determine the league champion.\n- **Rounds:** Usually include quarterfinals, semifinals, and finals, but the exact structure can vary based on league size.\n\n### **7. Scoring System**\nYahoo Fantasy Hockey offers both **head-to-head** and **points** scoring systems:\n- **Head-to-Head:** Teams face off each week against a single opponent in categories or total points.\n- **Points:** Each statistical achievement earns a set number of points, and the team with the most points at the end of the week wins.\n\n### **8. Season Length and Schedule**\n- **Start and End Dates:** Typically align with the NHL regular season, starting in early October and ending in late April.\n- **Games Per Week:** Depending on the league settings, teams may play every week or have scheduled matchups.\n\n### **9. Keeper and Dynasty Leagues**\n- **Keeper Leagues:** Allow managers to retain a certain number of players from one season to the next.\n- **Dynasty Leagues:** Managers keep their entire roster from year to year, simulating running an NHL team over multiple seasons.\n\n### **10. League Settings Customization**\nLeague commissioners can often customize:\n- **Scoring Settings:** Adjust points per goal, assist, etc.\n- **Roster Limits:** Set the number of active players, bench spots, and specific position requirements.\n- **Waiver Rules:** Determine how players are added and the priority system.\n- **Trade Rules:** Set limits on the number of trades per week or season.\n\n### **11. Tiebreakers**\nIn cases where teams are tied in standings, common tiebreakers include:\n- Total points scored throughout the season\n- Head-to-head record\n- Category performance if using categories\n\n### **Getting Started and Support**\nFor the most accurate and detailed rules, especially if you're joining a specific league, it's best to:\n- **Visit Yahoo Fantasy Hockey's Official Website:** [Yahoo Fantasy Sports](https://sports.yahoo.com/fantasy/)\n- **Consult the Help Center:** They offer comprehensive guides and FAQs.\n- **Communicate with Your League Commissioner:** Specific rules can vary, so ensure you understand your league\u2019s unique settings.\n\nBy familiarizing yourself with these general rules and exploring the specific settings of your league, you'll be well-equipped to manage your Yahoo Fantasy Hockey team effectively.",
